==Abstract==

This BIP defines <code>OP_OPTX_KNOT</code> (0xc0) and <code>OP_OPTX_KNOT_VERIFY</code> (0xc1), new script opcodes that verify knot-theoretic proof data appended to SegWit v2 P2MR transactions (BIP-360). The opcodes implement the GENSYS OPTX Topological Key Derivation Function (TKDF), which augments ML-DSA (CRYSTALS-Dilithium) signatures with a topologically-orthogonal hardness layer based on knot polynomial invariants.

==Motivation==

ML-DSA (CRYSTALS-Dilithium) signatures resist Shor's algorithm by reducing to the Module Learning With Errors (MLWE) and Module Short Integer Solution (MSIS) problems. However, a future quantum adversary that solves MLWE would break ML-DSA alone. <code>OP_OPTX_KNOT</code> adds a second cryptographic dimension: verification of knot polynomial invariants whose computation is PSPACE-hard in general, with no known quantum reduction to lattice problems.

This creates a composite security assumption: breaking OPTX requires simultaneously solving a lattice problem AND computing a non-trivial ambient-group isotopy invariant.

==Specification==

===Opcodes===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Opcode
! Hex
! Behavior
|-
| <code>OP_OPTX_KNOT</code>
| 0xc0
| Verify knot proof, push result to stack
|-
| <code>OP_OPTX_KNOT_VERIFY</code>
| 0xc1
| Verify knot proof, fail script if invalid
|}

===Stack Layout===

<pre>
<spatial_sig> <knot_data> <mldsa_pubkey> OP_OPTX_KNOT
</pre>

Where:

* <code><spatial_sig></code>: Serialized <code>SpatialSignature</code> (braid word + invariant suite + AGT tensor + commitment)
* <code><knot_data></code>: Serialized <code>KnotWitnessData</code> (see below)
* <code><mldsa_pubkey></code>: ML-DSA public key (1,312 bytes for Dilithium2)

===Knot Witness Data Format===

Wire format (all multi-byte integers are big-endian):

<pre>
[dt_code_len : 2 bytes] [dt_code : variable] [alpha_K : 16 bytes] [nu_K : 16 bytes] [writhe : 4 bytes]
</pre>

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Field
! Size
! Description
|-
| <code>dt_code_len</code>
| 2 bytes
| Length of DT code in bytes (uint16 BE)
|-
| <code>dt_code</code>
| variable
| Dowker-Thistlethwaite encoding of knot K
|-
| <code>alpha_K</code>
| 16 bytes
| Alexander polynomial eval at e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup> (IEEE 754 complex128 BE)
|-
| <code>nu_K</code>
| 16 bytes
| Jones polynomial eval at e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup> (IEEE 754 complex128 BE)
|-
| <code>writhe</code>
| 4 bytes
| Writhe number w(K) (int32 BE)
|}

Total additional witness overhead per input: ~48 bytes (+1.27% over baseline 3,772-byte Dilithium payload).

===Topological Key Derivation Function (TKDF)===

The TKDF computes:

<pre>
OPTX-KeyGen(K, s, n) = ML-DSA.KeyGen(H(alpha_K || nu_K || omega_K || s), n)
</pre>

Where:

* <code>alpha_K = Alexander(K, e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup>)</code> -- Alexander polynomial evaluation
* <code>nu_K = Jones(K, e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup>)</code> -- Jones polynomial evaluation
* <code>omega_K = writhe(K)</code> -- Writhe number
* <code>s</code> -- 256-bit entropy seed
* <code>H = SHAKE-256</code> with 512-bit output
* <code>n</code> -- ML-DSA security level (2, 3, or 5)

A domain separator <code>"OPTX-TKDF-v1.0\x00"</code> is prepended to the hash input to prevent cross-protocol attacks.

===Verification Rules===

Nodes running OPTX-aware software verify:

# <code>alpha_K == Alexander(parse_dt(dt_code), e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup>)</code>
# <code>nu_K == Jones(parse_dt(dt_code), e<sup>2{pi}i/n</sup>)</code>
# <code>writhe == compute_writhe(parse_dt(dt_code))</code>
# <code>H(alpha_K || nu_K || writhe || seed)</code> matches TKDF output
# Spatial signature invariant suite is internally consistent
# Complexity score >= MIN_MAINNET_COMPLEXITY (50)

